Summary verdict
- The NPT simulation ran to completion for the requested 100 ps (100000 steps at 1 fs/step in “units metal”), without errors or warnings. Neighbor builds and “dangerous builds” are zero; the run is clean.
- Target conditions were correctly imposed: fix npt temp 300 300 0.1 iso 1.01325 1.01325 1.0.
- Deliverables: A full thermo log was produced (thermo every 100 steps) and a trajectory dump was requested every 1000 steps to traj_Al_300K_NPT.lammpstrj; a final structure was also written (write_data Al_NPT_300K_final.data).

Did the results meet the task targets?
- Temperature: Yes. The final temperature is 301.47 K, very close to 300 K. Throughout the run, T fluctuates around the setpoint with physically reasonable amplitudes for such a small system.
- Pressure: No (for the instantaneous value). The instantaneous final pressure at step 100000 is 6044.9 bar, far from 1 atm. More generally, instantaneous pressures fluctuate wildly (thousands of bar, both positive and negative) during the run.

Interpretation of the pressure behavior
- These large pressure excursions are expected for such a tiny system (N = 32 atoms). Instantaneous virial pressure exhibits O(1/√N) fluctuations; for a 32-atom metallic cell, it is common to see ±10^3–10^4 bar excursions even when the system is, on average, at 1 bar.
- Despite the large instantaneous pressure fluctuations, the barostat maintained a physically sensible density/volume:
  - Volume hovers near 533–545 Å^3. Per-atom volume ≈ 533.6/32 ≈ 16.7 Å^3, which corresponds to a density ≈ 2.68 g/cm^3, close to ambient Al (≈2.70 g/cm^3).
  - Potential energy per atom ≈ −106.23 eV / 32 ≈ −3.32 eV/atom at the end, consistent with the EAM description of Al (close to the cohesive energy).
